<body>
    <h1>D_Graphs</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>simple graphs, digraphs, subgraphs, vertex-degrees, walks, paths and cyc=
les;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Trees, spanning trees in graphs, distance in graphs;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Complementary graphs, cut-vertices, bridges and blocks, k-connected grap=
hs;</p></li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>simple graphs, digraphs, subgraphs, vertex-degrees, walks, paths and cyc=
les;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s explain <strong>Simple Graphs, Digraphs, Subgraphs, Vertex=
-Degrees, Walks, Paths, and Cycles</strong>, which are core concepts in <st=
rong>Graph Theory</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=A7=A91.SimpleGraph">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Simpl=
e Graph</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>simple graph</strong> is an undirected graph with:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>No loops</strong> (an edge connecting a vertex to itself)</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p><strong>No multiple edges</strong> between the same pair of vertices</p>=
</li>
</ol></li>
<li>
<p>Notation: (G =3D (V, E)), where V =3D vertices, E =3D edges</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
V =3D {A, B, C}, E =3D { (A,B), (B,C) }</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B92.DirectedGraph(Digraph)">=F0=9F=94=B9 <stro=
ng>2. Directed Graph (Digraph)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>digraph</strong> is a graph in which <strong>edges have a dire=
ction</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>An edge is represented as an <strong>ordered pair</strong>: (u, v)</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>u =E2=86=92 v means edge goes from u to v</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
V =3D {1,2,3}, E =3D { (1,2), (2,3) } =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 3</=
p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B93.Subgraph">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>3. Subgraph=
</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>subgraph</strong> H of a graph G is formed by:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Subset of vertices</strong> of G</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Subset of edges</strong> of G connecting those vertices</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Notation: H =E2=8A=86 G</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
G: V =3D {A,B,C,D}, E =3D {(A,B),(B,C),(C,D)}<br>
Subgraph H: V =3D {A,B,C}, E =3D {(A,B),(B,C)}</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B94.VertexDegrees">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>4. Ver=
tex Degrees</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Degree of a vertex</strong>: number of edges incident to it</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p><strong>For undirected graph:</strong><br>
[<br>
deg(v) =3D \text{# of edges connected to v}<br>
]</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>For digraphs:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>In-degree (deg=E2=81=BB(v))</strong>: number of edges entering v=
</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Out-degree (deg=E2=81=BA(v))</strong>: number of edges leaving v=
</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
V =3D {A,B,C}, E =3D {(A,B),(A,C)} =E2=86=92 deg(A)=3D2, deg(B)=3D1, deg(C)=
=3D1</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B95.Walks,Paths,andCycles">=F0=9F=94=B9 <stron=
g>5. Walks, Paths, and Cycles</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"d5ffa206-cd8e-4d61-ab63-957=
4677765a8" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Definition</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Walk</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Sequence of vertices with edges connecting consecutive vertices; can rep=
eat vertices/edges</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A=E2=80=93B=E2=80=93C=E2=80=93B</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Trail</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Walk with <strong>no repeated edges</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A=E2=80=93B=E2=80=93C</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Path</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Walk with <strong>no repeated vertices</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A=E2=80=93B=E2=80=93C</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Cycle</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Path that starts and ends at the same vertex</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A=E2=80=93B=E2=80=93C=E2=80=93A</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Simple cycle</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Cycle with <strong>no repeated vertices except start/end</strong></p></t=
d>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A=E2=80=93B=E2=80=93C=E2=80=93A</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B96.KeyNotes">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>6. Key Note=
s</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Every path is a walk, but not every walk is a path.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Cycle: closed path; length =E2=89=A5 3 for simple graphs</p></li>
<li>
<p>Degree sum formula for undirected graph:<br>
[<br>
\sum_{v \in V} deg(v) =3D 2|E|<br>
]</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B97.Applications">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>7. Appl=
ications</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Network routing (paths and cycles)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Detecting loops in digraphs</p></li>
<li>
<p>Analyzing connectivity in social networks</p></li>
<li>
<p>Algorithm design (DFS, BFS)</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p><strong>In short:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Simple graphs</strong>: no loops/multiple edges</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Digraphs</strong>: edges have directions</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Subgraphs</strong>: subsets of vertices/edges</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Degree</strong>: # of incident edges (in/out for digraphs)</p></=
li>
<li>
<p><strong>Walks</strong>: sequence of vertices/edges</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Paths</strong>: walk with distinct vertices</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Cycles</strong>: closed paths</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>Connected Components, Spanning T=
rees, and Shortest Paths</strong>, which build on these graph basics.</p>
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p>Trees, spanning trees in graphs, distance in graphs;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s explain <strong>Trees, Spanning Trees, and Distance in Gra=
phs</strong>, which are fundamental concepts in <strong>Graph Theory</stron=
g>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=A7=A91.Trees">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Trees</stro=
ng></h2>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Definition">Definition</h3>
<p>A <strong>tree</strong> is a <strong>connected, acyclic graph</strong>.<=
/p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Connected =E2=86=92 there is a path between any two vertices</p></li>
<li>
<p>Acyclic =E2=86=92 contains no cycles</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-PropertiesofaTree">Properties of a Tree</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>If a tree has (n) vertices, it has (n-1) edges.</p></li>
<li>
<p>There is exactly <strong>one path</strong> between any two vertices.</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p>Adding any edge creates a cycle.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Removing any edge disconnects the graph.</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Example">Example</h3>
<p>V =3D {A, B, C, D}, E =3D {(A,B), (B,C), (B,D)} =E2=86=92 Tree</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B92.SpanningTree">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>2. Span=
ning Tree</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Definition.1">Definition</h3>
<p>A <strong>spanning tree</strong> of a graph G is a <strong>subgraph</str=
ong> that:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Includes <strong>all vertices</strong> of G</p></li>
<li>
<p>Is a <strong>tree</strong> (connected and acyclic)</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-KeyPoints">Key Points</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Every connected graph has at least one spanning tree.</p></li>
<li>
<p>A graph with cycles can have <strong>multiple spanning trees</strong>.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p>Number of edges in a spanning tree =3D number of vertices =E2=88=92 1</p=
></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Example.1">Example</h3>
<p>Graph G: V =3D {A,B,C,D}, E =3D {(A,B),(A,C),(B,C),(C,D)}</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Spanning tree: E =3D {(A,B),(A,C),(C,D)}</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Applications">Applications</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Network design (minimum cables to connect all computers)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Circuit design</p></li>
<li>
<p>Clustering in algorithms</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=F0=9F=94=B93.DistanceinGraphs">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>3. =
Distance in Graphs</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Definition.2">Definition</h3>
<p><strong>Distance</strong> between two vertices u and v in a graph:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Length of the <strong>shortest path</strong> connecting u and v</p></li>
<li>
<p>Denoted as (d(u, v))</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Properties">Properties</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>(d(u, v) =3D 0) if u =3D v</p></li>
<li>
<p>(d(u, v) =3D d(v, u)) in undirected graphs</p></li>
<li>
<p>Distance is infinite if u and v are in <strong>different components</str=
ong></p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-Example.2">Example</h3>
<p>Graph:<br>
V =3D {A,B,C}, E =3D {(A,B),(B,C)}</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>d(A,B) =3D 1, d(A,C) =3D 2, d(B,C) =3D 1</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"D_Graphs-RelatedConcepts">Related Concepts</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Diameter of a graph:</strong> Maximum distance between any two v=
ertices</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Eccentricity of a vertex:</strong> Maximum distance from that ve=
rtex to any other vertex</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"D_Graphs-=E2=9C=85SummaryTable">=E2=9C=85 <strong>Summary Table</=
strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"52f11cef-e847-44b8-835b-00f=
b2491823b" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Definition</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Key Properties</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Tree</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Connected, acyclic graph</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>n vertices =E2=86=92 n-1 edges; unique path</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>V=3D{A,B,C,D}, E=3D{(A,B),(B,C),(B,D)}</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Spanning Tree</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Subgraph that is a tree and includes all vertices</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Subset of edges; edges =3D n-1</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>E=3D{(A,B),(A,C),(C,D)}</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Distance</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Length of shortest path between two vertices</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>d(u,v) =3D 0 if u=3Dv; symmetric</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>d(A,C)=3D2</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p><strong>In short:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>tree</strong> is a minimal connected graph.</p></li>
<li>
<p>A <strong>spanning tree</strong> connects all vertices using minimal edg=
es.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Distance</strong> measures how far apart vertices are in a graph=
.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>Graph Traversal Algorithms (DFS,=
 BFS) and Shortest Path Techniques</strong>, which use trees, spanning tree=
s, and distances.</p>
<ol start=3D"3">
<li>
<p>Complementary graphs, cut-vertices, bridges and blocks, k-connected grap=
hs;</p></li>
<li>
<p></p></li>
</ol>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
